===Etymology 2===
Anglo-French ''[[russher]]'', ''[[russer]]'', French ''[[ruser]]''. Confer Middle High German ''[[ruschen]]'', German ''[[rauschen]]'', Dutch ''[[ruischen]]''.

====Adjective====
'''rush''' (''no [[comparative]] or [[superlative]]''; ''used only before a noun'')

#[[Perform]]ed with, or [[requiring]] [[urgency]] or great haste, or done under [[pressure]].
#:''rush job''

====Noun====
'''rush''' (''plural'' '''rushes''')

#A [[sudden]] [[forward]] [[motion]].
#A [[surge]].
#General [[haste]].
#(''military'') A sudden [[attack]]; an [[onslaught]].
#A [[rapid]], noisy [[flow]].
#(''[[football]]'') the [[act]] of running at another [[player]] to [[block]] or [[disrupt]] play.<!--what kind of football?  Soccer or American football-->
#A [[pleasurable]] [[sensation]] [[experience]]d after [[use]] of a [[stimulant]], etc.
#A sudden, [[brief]] [[exhilaration]].
#(''US'') A regulated period of recruitment in [[fraternity|fraternities]] and [[sorority|sororities]].

